# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 8th-meridian-east
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:8th-meridian-east/100th-meridian-west] The **meridian 100° west** of the Prime Meridian of Greenwich is a line of longitude that extends from the North Pole across the Arctic Ocean, North America, the Pacific Ocean, the Southern Ocean, and Antarctica to the South Pole.
[src:8th-meridian-east/100th-meridian-west] The 100th meridian west forms a great circle with the 80th meridian east.
[src:8th-meridian-east/100th-meridian-west] In the United States, this meridian roughly marks the boundary between the semi-arid climate in the west and the humid continental and humid subtropical climates in the east, and as such roughly connotes the regions of the Eastern and the Western United States.
[src:8th-meridian-east/100th-meridian-west] In the United States the meridian 100° west of Greenwich forms the eastern border of the Texas panhandle with Oklahoma (which traces its origin to the Adams-Onís Treaty in 1819 which settled the border between New Spain and the United States between the Red River and Arkansas River).
[src:8th-meridian-east/100th-meridian-west] Dodge City, Kansas lies exactly at the intersection of the Arkansas River and the 100th meridian.
[src:8th-meridian-east/100th-meridian-west] As first noted by John Wesley Powell in the 1870s, there is a big difference in rainfall by the different sides of the meridian.
[src:8th-meridian-east/100th-meridian-west] West of the meridian, raising livestock is much more economically important than east of it, and what agriculture does exist relies heavily on irrigation.
[src:8th-meridian-east/100th-meridian-west] Historically, the meridian has often been taken as a rough boundary between the eastern and western United States.
[src:8th-meridian-east/100th-meridian-west] White settlement, spreading westward after the American Civil War, settled the area around this meridian during the 1870s.
[src:8th-meridian-east/100th-meridian-west] Highway 30 in Cozad, Nebraska, marks the place where the 100th meridian intersects with the routes of the Oregon Trail, Pony Express, transcontinental railroad, and the Lincoln Highway.
[src:8th-meridian-east/105th-meridian-west] The **meridian 105° west of Greenwich** is a line of longitude that extends from the North Pole across the Arctic Ocean, North America, the Pacific Ocean, the Southern Ocean, and Antarctica to the South Pole.
[src:8th-meridian-east/105th-meridian-west] The 105th meridian west forms a great circle with the 75th meridian east.
[src:8th-meridian-east/105th-meridian-west] It serves as the reference meridian for the seventh time zone west of Greenwich, known as UTC-07 or the Mountain Time Zone in North America.
[src:8th-meridian-east/105th-meridian-west] In the United States, Interstate Highway I-25 roughly parallels the meridian from Douglas, Wyoming to Las Vegas, New Mexico, and from Wellington, Colorado to the Prospect Road interchange (in Fort Collins, Colorado), I-25 happens to be almost exactly aligned along the 105th meridian west.
[src:8th-meridian-east/105th-meridian-west] The meridian bisects Denver, Colorado, passing through Denver Union Station.
[src:8th-meridian-east/105th-meridian-west] Throughout the Denver metro area, Kalamath Street is the road that most closely corresponds to the 105th meridian.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-meridian-east] The **meridian 10° east of Greenwich** is a line of longitude that extends from the North Pole across the Arctic Ocean, Europe, Africa, the Atlantic Ocean, the Southern Ocean, and Antarctica to the South Pole.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-meridian-east] The 10th meridian east forms a great circle with the 170th meridian west.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-meridian-east] In some world maps, the 10th Meridian East is used the centre (instead of Greenwich), to avoid cutting off the tip of Asia.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-meridian-west] The **meridian 10° west of Greenwich** is a line of longitude that extends from the North Pole across the Arctic Ocean, the Atlantic Ocean, Ireland, Africa, the Southern Ocean, and Antarctica to the South Pole.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-meridian-west] The 10th meridian west forms a great circle with the 170th meridian east.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-meridian-west] This longitude is the eastern limit of the Atlântico Brasileiro, Montevideo, Ezeiza and Comodoro Rivadavia flight information regions, as well as the western limit of the Luanda and Johannesburg Oceanic FIRs.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-meridian-west] The meridian defines the western limit of the New Swabia area in Queen Maud Land, Antarctica.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-north] The **6th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 6 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-north] It crosses Africa, the Indian Ocean, Southeast Asia, the Pacific Ocean, South America, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-north] Damage from the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami was concentrated at this latitude.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-north] The **7th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 7 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-north] It crosses Africa, the Indian Ocean, South Asia, Southeast Asia, the Pacific Ocean, South America, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-north] The **8th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 8 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-north] It crosses Africa, the Indian Ocean, South Asia, Southeast Asia, the Pacific Ocean, Central America, South America, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-north] The parallel defines part of the border between Somalia and Ethiopia.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-north] The Eight Degree Channel (Maliku Kandu) in the Indian Ocean is named after the parallel.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-north] The **9th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 9 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-north] The **10th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 10 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-north] It crosses Africa, the Indian Ocean, the Indian subcontinent, Southeast Asia, the Pacific Ocean, Central America, South America, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 12 hours, 43 minutes during the summer solstice and 11 hours, 33 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-north] On 21 June, the maximum altitude of the sun is 103.44 degrees and 56.56 degrees on 21 December.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-north] In this case an angle larger than 90° means that the culmination takes place at a maximum altitude of 76.56 degrees in the opposite cardinal direction.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-north] In the northern torrid zone, the Sun remains in the south during winter, but can reach over the zenith to the north in midsummer.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-north] A section of the border between Guinea and Sierra Leone is defined by the parallel.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-north] The Ten Degree Channel in the Indian Ocean is named after the parallel.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-north] In the end of part two of the Spanish television heist crime drama series *La casa de papel*, a point near Palawan island, Philippines, with the coordinates of 10th parallel north and 118,5º, was the meeting point of *El Professor* and *Raquel* one year after the heist.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-south] The **6th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 6 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-south] It crosses the Atlantic Ocean, Africa, the Indian Ocean, Southeast Asia, Australasia, the Pacific Ocean and South America.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-south] The **7th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 7 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-south] Part of the border between the Democratic Republic of the Congo and Angola is defined by the parallel.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-south] It is the most populous parallel south of the Equator, being home to between 86.1 million and 99.8 million people as of 2019.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-south] The **8th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 8 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-south] Two sections of the border between the Democratic Republic of the Congo and Angola are defined by the parallel.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-south] It passes through 10 out of the 26 states of Brazil.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-south] The **9th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 9 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-south] It crosses the Atlantic Ocean, Africa, the Indian Ocean, Australasia, the Pacific Ocean and South America.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-south] The parallel passes through 11 out of the 26 states of Brazil.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-south] The **10th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 10 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:8th-meridian-east/10th-parallel-south] Part of the border between Brazil and Peru is defined by the parallel.
[src:8th-meridian-east/110th-meridian-west] The **meridian 110° west of Greenwich** is a line of longitude that extends from the North Pole across the Arctic Ocean, North America, the Pacific Ocean, the Southern Ocean, and Antarctica to the South Pole.
[src:8th-meridian-east/110th-meridian-west] The 110th meridian west forms a great circle with the 70th meridian east.
[src:8th-meridian-east/110th-meridian-west] In Canada, the meridian forms the boundary between Nunavut and the Northwest Territories north of the parallel 70° north.
[src:8th-meridian-east/110th-meridian-west] Originally 110°W was intended as the Fourth Meridian for the Dominion Land Survey, but because of the imperfect surveying methods of the time, the meridian was placed a few hundred metres west of this longitude.
[src:8th-meridian-east/110th-meridian-west] The Fourth Meridian has been the entire boundary between Alberta and Saskatchewan since 1905.
[src:8th-meridian-east/110th-meridian-west] In the United States, the meridian formed the western border of the historic and extralegal Territory of Jefferson.
[src:8th-meridian-east/8th-meridian-east] The **meridian 8° east of Greenwich** is a line of longitude that extends from the North Pole across the Arctic Ocean, Europe, Africa, the Atlantic Ocean, the Southern Ocean, and Antarctica to the South Pole.
[src:8th-meridian-east/8th-meridian-east] The 8th meridian east forms a great circle with the 172nd meridian west.
